I"ù<p>Continuous-state <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">dynamical systems</a> are as diverse as <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/finite-state-dynamical-systems-are-diverse">finite-state ones</a>. They can either use <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/tense-logic-formalizes-time">discrete</a> or continuous <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/time-is-a-relevant-dimension-of-attention">time</a>, and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dynamical-systems-have-a-certain-anatomy">share the same basic anatomy</a>, although using <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/embeddings-in-machine-learning-represent-prototypes-or-exemplars">continuous states</a>. For the ones with continuous time, the transition function yields <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/differential-equations-can-be-ordinary-or-partial">rates of change</a>, rather than absolute values. They all exhibit typical behaviors: <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/attractors-and-repellors-have-opposite-behaviors-in-dynamical-systems">attractors and repellors</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/bifurcations-segment-space-of-dynamical-systems-in-basins">bifurcation</a>, and chaos.</p>
